            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-12-12T17:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-12-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="96" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d96">
                <head>96. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On June 13, at the 326th meeting of the National Security Council, the President
                    presiding, <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen Dulles</persName> in his review of
                    significant world developments affecting United States security, raised the
                    question of Jordan and the potential threats to King <persName
                        corresp="#p_Hussein1">Hussein</persName> and King <persName
                        corresp="#p_EMJSD1">Saud</persName>. The memorandum of discussion includes
                    the following exchange: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The Director of Central Intelligence said he would first deal with
                            developments in the Middle East. Of recent days, <persName
                                corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName> had lost a great deal of
                            ground and standing in the Arab world. King <persName
                                corresp="#p_EMJSD1">Saud</persName> was still in Amman. King
                                <persName corresp="#p_Hussein1">Hussein</persName> had all but
                            broken diplomatic relations with Egypt following his expulsion of two
                            Egyptian diplomats from Jordan…. Nevertheless, continued Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>, we cannot but worry about
                                <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName>’s possible reaction
                            to these recent reverses. We believe that he is still plotting to do
                            away with King <persName corresp="#p_EMJSD1">Saud</persName> and King
                                <persName corresp="#p_Hussein1">Hussein</persName>, and both are in
                            genuine danger.</p>
                        <p>“Meanwhile, President <persName corresp="#p_aQS1">Kuwatly</persName> of
                            Syria has been visiting in Egypt. It is not clear what has transpired in
                            the course of this visit. There are, however, indications of further
                            Saudi rapprochement with Iraq. With regard to the recent resignation of
                            the government of Nuri Said in Iraq, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                                >Dulles</persName> predicted that Nuri would probably be <pb
                                facs="0178" n="146" xml:id="pg_146"/> persuaded to resume the office
                            of Prime Minister. There seemed no particular reason for his resignation
                            except the desire for a rest.</p>
                        <p>“Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> broke in to
                            comment that in recent days <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1"
                                >Nasser</persName> had grown increasingly bitter, and that he was
                            blaming the United States in general and Secretary <persName
                                corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> in particular for everything
                            that had gone wrong. This was illustrated by <persName
                                corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName>’s article in <hi rend="italic"
                                >Look</hi> magazine. <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1"
                            >Nasser</persName>’s attitude seemed to Secretary <persName
                                corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> to be rather ironical, in view
                            of the direction of U.S. policy when Egypt was invaded last November;
                            although, admittedly, the prime motivation of our actions last autumn
                            was not the desire to cultivate the friendship of <persName
                                corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName> and of Egypt.” (Eisenhower
                            Library, Whitman File, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Records)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
